Use one shared backend context, then choose the handle by authority boundary:

```ts
// Authenticated API request: caller permissions and caller authorship
const db = await jazz.forRequest(request);

// System cron job: backend authority and system authorship
const db = jazz.asBackend();

// Webhook: backend permissions but user authorship
const db = await jazz.withAttributionForRequest(request);
// or, if the webhook already resolved the user:
const db = jazz.withAttribution(userId);
```

Use `forRequest` when row policies must authorise the user. Use `withAttribution*` only for trusted server work where backend authority is intentional but audit/provenance should name the user.

Create a single persistent Node.js context in a server-only module and reuse it:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency. Use a stable `dataPath`; `{ type: "memory" }` is ephemeral and needs an upstream `serverUrl`. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only, never public-prefixed. Use `backendSecret` for server-connected backend/scoped handles. Shut the context down on process exit with `await jazz.shutdown()`, and explicitly wait for the required durability tier before an endpoint reports success.

For reactive query inputs, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the query when inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);
```

Solid:
```ts
const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current input value instead of tracking later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two writes that should become optimistically visible together in the UI.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the writes must remain staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Define the initial schema with an optional self-reference column. A `managerId` ref creates the typed forward relation `manager`.

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

type AppSchema = s.Schema<typeof schema>;
export const app: s.App<AppSchema> = s.defineApp(schema);
```

Use a timestamp/date column for the event time, an inline binary column for a small fingerprint that should load with the row, and a typed ref for the project relation.

```ts
const schema = {
  projects: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
  }),
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.date(),
    fingerprint: s.bytes(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),
  }),
};
```

Use chunked file/blob storage only for larger data that should not always travel with the row.

Create the file with an edge write tier, then create the parent only after that settles, also waiting at edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label,
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download, request the required tier and distinguish missing access from incomplete chunks:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  return blob;
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) return { state: "not-found" };
  if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) return { state: "incomplete", reason: error.reason };
  throw error;
}
```

Treat `IncompleteFileDataError` as a retriable or repair-needed product state; a stronger read tier can wait for remote data, but it will not fix corrupt metadata or a genuinely missing part.

Keep the parent row until inherited delete permissions have been used. Load the upload, load its file, delete every part, delete the file row, then delete the upload row:

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });

if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete `uploads` first, because `files` and `file_parts` usually inherit delete authorisation through `uploads.fileId` and `files.partIds`.

Use a real local sync server and compare normalised results, not raw query order. Insert the rows on client A, wait for edge durability, then poll client B until the same set is visible.

```ts
const created = await Promise.all(
  ["alpha", "bravo", "charlie"].map((title) =>
    alice.insert(app.todos, { title, done: false }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
  ),
);

const expected = created
  .map(({ id, title, done }) => ({ id, title, done }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

await vi.waitFor(async () => {
  const rows = await bob.all(app.todos, { tier: "edge" });
  const actual = rows
    .filter((row) => expected.some((item) => item.id === row.id))
    .map(({ id, title, done }) => ({ id, title, done }))
    .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

  expect(actual).toEqual(expected);
});
```

This keeps the test black-boxed and deterministic: edge waits establish durability, `vi.waitFor` handles eventual delivery, and sorting by stable `id` avoids testing unspecified row ordering.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the policy is exercised through public APIs. Assert denied reads as missing rows and denied writes as rejected operations.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
  const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

  const row = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private todo", done: false }).value;

  await expect(bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Bob should not write" }),
  );

  alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, row.id, { title: "Alice can still write" }),
  );
});
```

If the policy also controls deletes or inserts, add separate assertions for those operations rather than assuming update coverage proves them.
